Gibson said he had to leave watching it because it was so close and has also cited Escape From New York, Mike Pondsmith has cited them as well as Streets of Fire
Part of the look of the film is inspired by the necessity to hide the fact that they were filming on the Warners backlot and the buildings had been seen hundreds of times before and were only two stories tall with the Hollywood Hills behind them and so that is where the nighttime photography with a lot of shadows and rain and smoke comes from to conceal the limitations and break up the familiarity, but also Ridley Scott himself has said the built up decaying look was partly inspired by the comic The Long Tomorrow that appeared in Heavy Metal, by Dan O'Bannon and Moebius and he gave copies to the art department. He would also show them Edward Hoppers painting Nighthawks too.
But you cant say Blade Runner invented it, there is proto-cyberpunk clearly visible in the works of Alfred Bester and Philip K. Dick

>>179104041

>stay true to the spirit of the originals while also poking fun at them

Yes, the goofball nerd pointing out the uselessness of the kaiju powers was well done, when that kind of joke usually falls flat in most snarky observational humor.

Personally, I wasn't a fan of the kaijus (like the Evas in the rebuilds, they just look and move unnaturally, like all japanese CGI really). All the mocaped humans looked amazing though. Ultraman himself just has this presence and posture that really shines through.

Glancing briefly at Wikipedia, I'm getting the sense that they actually condensed the whole 39-episode story of the original show down into a 2-hour film (at least looking at character names and episode titles). It was extremely well paced and didn't feel unnaturally stunted in the story department. Ultraman's conversations with each of the successive villains was great. It was just enough of the Anno life philosophy stuff without shoving it down your throat like Eva.

Speaking of Eva, I noticed that Anno couldn't resist throwing in a couple minutes of incomprehensible technobabble. At least it wasn't for 20 minutes like in 3.00+1.0 (SEVEN SPEARS?).

Overall, good job Anno.

Or just accept that crab walking will always look ridiculous because our fear of a monster is a fear of a predator and we all subconsciously know how a non-bipedal predator is structured skeletal and musculature wise. A creature that has a build like a crab walker would inherently be slow, clumsy, and not much of a threat to both prey and non-prey species. It would simply lack leverage and the ability to exert explosive energy and even the dumb mother fucker alive today has an ingrained part of their lizard brain that recognizes that. The superficial characteristics of a monster are interchangeable but if you're intending to scare audiences you have to adhere to the logic of how an actual successful predator species would be built structurally.

There's really only two issues, and neither of them break the film, they're each just a nuisance at best. One is the kids constantly running into each other and the villain, this is only a major issue if you're a turbo autist that can't handle the slightest bit of convenient writing without screaming about the film being contrived.

The other is the way they handle the entire sequence from Kiri having her seizure to Norm and Max showing up on the heli to Quaritch picking up the signal. The way it's shown makes you wonder "hold on, did they bring her back, and then call norm and max, who rushed all the way to the metkayina village, failed to resuscitate Kiri, and THEN ronal showed up and fixed her up in a couple minutes? why didn't they just talk to ronal right away when they got back? they wouldn't have risked tipping off quaritch and it would've all made a lot more sense." This could've been easily solved with one or two really quick shots added - you show that Kiri had her seizure, the kids brought her back to camp, and then ronal began treating her right away, but when Kiri wouldn't wake up, Jake grows desperate and quickly calls Max and Norm on a secure line, and they both fly out immediately with all the equipment they can grab to treat Kiri. Then while ronal is preparing some medicine, they both come in to take some samples and run some tests, which pisses off ronal, and the rest of the sequence continues as it was written in the film. Another, cheaper, and in my opinion much smoother option, would be to not have Max And Norm fly out at all, and just have Jake reach out to them with a Skype call while ronal treats Kiri so they can do a remote consultation of sorts, and then the call gets intercepted by quaritch somehow. This would lose the visual visceral connection that audiences can make between seeing Norm and Max arrive at the village with their helicopter and then Quaritch picking up their tracks, but it would make the "plot" smoother.

Not to be rude or anything, but time is a very prevalent theme in this movie:
>amrita stopping aging
>kids growing old
>unspecified timeskips
>Jake and the kids taking their TIME to learn the way of water
>the way of water focuses on birth and death, consequences of the passage of time
>the way Ronal's babybump grows with time
>the eclipses that happen at a certain TIME of day
It's perfectly reasonable that this whole Ronal's medicine ordeal was merely a deliberate play on themes, which is not unusual for Cameron to do. It seems that he takes this to the next level, and really tries to challenge your conception of chronology, by making you question how much time had indeed passed between Kiri's accident and Ronal's aide. She very probably spent many hours looking for the correct medicine, ie plants or certain bugs. She probably even took her sweet time to sharpen that little pokey thing she poked Kiri's peachfuzz-having tummy with. It's perfectly reasonable that she stopped the ingredient picking to think if it was really worth it, we know she has a temper and probably, canonically most likely, BPD. All we know is, probably as much as a helicopter ride from the good humans' base to there, which could be days, and it would still make sense. Non issue. Archived.

posts.com:
Autistic complaint but I'm a little sore that the JPIII section of the Lego game is kinda gutted and unfaithful to the film.
What I mean is, the adaptations of JP and TLW both nail the atmosphere when it's not being
>le funny toy bricks
in a way that almost feels ripped straight from the films. The aesthetics,t he lighting, the atmosphere, it's all there. JPIII's levels don't really have that.
In their respective hub worlds, you can visit nearly every iconic setpiece that happens on the islands, except for JPIII. There's no air strip, you can't actually go into the lab, there's no river, stuff like that.
In the level based of the Spino vs T. rex fight, you have to help the T. rex defeat the Spino in order to get away.
They have the licensed music for the first two films, even Jurassic World's but there's a completely generic score on top of JPIII.
There's no Ceratosaurus. In fact, they had a whole slot they could have used for it, but instead they gave it to Baryonyx, which was never even in any of the films at that point.
Steven Spielberg and Colin Trevorrow get playable characters but not Joe Johnston.

The guys working on this game really didn't like JPIII and I think it's a disgrace, because they'll go all out for the Star Wars sequels but I can't even get a faithful representation of JPIII? Fuck outta here.
Had some great moments though, weebum related.

Thank you for listening to my sperg rant. Hope a fellow JP fanatic can relate.

>>179114048
Harry Potter revitalized/created the YA book series as we know it, which prompted the success of other series, like The Hunger Games and Twilight. Harry Potter was a cultural phenomenon that paved the way for other successful series to take off. That success is what prompted studios to take a chance on adaptations and spurred a run of box office successes for YA series.

You also have to consider than the Harry Potter film series ran alongside, at the start, LOTR. That reinforced the fantasy genre generally AND allowed Harry Potter to solidly have the YA track.
It’s significantly harder now to have the type of all-encompassing cultural phenomenon that Harry Potter was. Our culture is far more fractured (which has good points—More people can find their niche). And the rise of TV means that whether you are talking an original work or a book adaptation, a popular YA story might end up as a TV show, not a box office hit.

And culturally, the MCU largely fills the role that those YA works did. There might not be a lane for a YA sci fi and fantasy series when the MCU is close enough.
And there’s the compounded problem of what YA is—The film series you listed were all sci fi and fantasy, but YA books cover more genres. Maybe the next major YA series ends up being a surprise blockbuster like a teen romance or horror series instead.

There’s always a chance that a major YA hit could emerge, but it’s much harder to predict in the current market.

>>179114742
Gosling's read that the character is just a guy who's seen too many movies seems off at first, but the more I think about it the more sense it makes and the more it dovetails with everything else.

The movie essentially serves as a thought experiment where a man was everything cool, except for any of the basic, uncool, day to day emotional makings of happiness. Maybe as opposed to being a guy who's seen too many movies exactly, he is a guy from movies who has been transported to emotional reality-normal human loneliness begins to set in and he can't understand it because as far as he's consciously concerned he has everything he needs and he is doing what it makes sense to do.

His longing for something else in the movie is palpable as part of a juxtaposition between how men want to present themselves, and what they truly want, and how difficult it is to admit to yourself and others what you want, the tension of having to move away from your desired self image to the vulnerability and humbleness of pursuing real connection. But also how hollow the image men want for themselves is.

In this context a "hero" is not just a cool guy, it is a means of trying to square the circle. If you don't think you can be lastingly happy anyway, or can't sacrifice other patterns of life and habits of self presentation towards it, or if you just don't now, you can be a hero. You can go die as an act of love, for another individual or for the world in general that still reads as cool. This is why it's a happy ending. The Driver could not be someone in a lasting, loving relationship, but he could die as a gesture of love that validated and consummated all his longing and interior depth of feeling.

>>179115134
Incidentally the "literally me" phenomenon especially among lets, just cut out the middle-man and say autistic males is not some cringe conceit where they think they're cool, it is a very natural parrelel. Just as the driver has a personality based on movies, autistic people often learn how to behave from media, because it is approachable in a safe environment and does not depend on their weird input as a derailing factor. And while this helps to a degree, it leaves them not quite right in their interactions with the world. They talk different and have different standards for what's normal or desirable based on what they've seen on tv.

So just as the driver is trapped and unable to escape movie mode despite his unexpected yearnings for love, the autistic person is in fact often of an affectionate disposition, interested in the world, not even resentful, but just doesn't know how to act out love towards it, leaving a full consumation with the world out of their reach even if they are fundamentally nice, non-embittered guys. There's a natural parrelel there-wanting something but not knowing quite how to act-like when the driver stomps the guys head out of love, not thinking for a moment that she would react how she did. Drive appeals not to the bitterness of that situation, but to the fantasy of overcoming it, even if only through the simplicity of killing the right person or dying the right way, of carrying out an action that proves your love and interior validity and depth of existence in spite of your inability to express it, evidence it, or live it day to day.

Of course all the above goes for men in general, even the non autistic males are socialized towards the calloused, stoic, aversion to vulnerability that's talked about ad nauseum and which can easily sabotage relationships because you can't just turn it off at will, but the above probably explains its particular appeal to 4chan

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I don't like slow zombies because they aren't a threat besides the initial breakout if the characters don't know what zombies are.

It always comes down to human vs human conflict in the end while fast zombies are such a giant threat that you can sustain an entire movie with just them as an antagonist.

Dawn of the Dead (2004) is a classic and I feel bad about zoomers watching it in todays time.

You need to realize that Japanese horror like The Ring and Grudge were the big horror thing at the time and Dawn of the Dead legitimately fooled every cinema-goer into thinking it would be small scale home setting with a creepy daughter zombie at the start.

Then the woman escapes the bathroom and you see the entire world going to shit. This wasn't done on this scale before in 2004. That unraveling is what single-handedly ushered in the apocalypse and zombie hype that was sustained until the mid 2010s.

I still think to this day that Dark of the Dead is one of the most influential films in cinema history with the biggest impact on the media landscape in general.

>>179115405
That was done for both Knives Out, Chip 'n Dale Rescue Rangers 2022, and Everything Everywhere All at Once.
Studio Ghibli is the one that started this trend, adding a 35mm film grain/gate weave effect in all of their digital films (starting with My Neighbors the Yamadas and Spirited Away).
Netflix's The Cuphead Show! also did this.

A more complex way to do this is to print out the digital footage to 35mm film, which is what Dune 2021 and The Batman 2022 did.
